properties.long_name: Extent of the Roman Republic, 298 B.C.
properties.rulers: Lucius Cornelius Scipio Barbatus; Gnaeus Fulvius Maximus Centumalus
properties.event1:
Samnite Wars: Rome declared war on the Samnites after an appeal by the Lucani.
Rome captured the Samnite cities of Bojano and Castel di Sangro.
properties.title_header: Year of the Consulship of Barbatus and Centumalus

properties.long_name: Extent of the Roman Republic, 264 B.C.
properties.rulers: Appius Claudius Caudex; Marcus Fulvius Flaccus
properties.event1:
The Roman consul Appius Claudius Caudex and his two legions are deployed to Sicily, the first time a Roman army has gone into action outside the Italian peninsula.
Battle of Messana: A Roman force defeated a Carthaginian and Siracusani garrison at Messina.
properties.title_header: Year of the Consulship of Caudex and Flaccus

properties.long_name: Extent of the Roman Republic, 218 B.C.
properties.rulers: Publius Cornelius Scipio; Tiberius Sempronius Longus
properties.event1:
Second Punic War: A Carthaginian army departed Cartagena.
Illyrian Wars: Demetrius of Pharos fled to Macedonia.
properties.title_header: Year of the Consulship of Scipio and Longus

properties.long_name: Extent of the Roman Republic, 290 B.C.
properties.rulers: Publius Cornelius Rufinus; Manius Curius Dentatus
properties.event1:
Roman general and consul, Manius Curius Dentatus, gains a decisive victory over the Samnites, thereby ending a war that has lasted 50 years.
He also reduces the Sabine insurgents to submission, their territory is annexed and they are granted civitas sine suffragio ("citizenship without the right to vote").
properties.title_header: Year of the Consulship of Rufinus and Dentatus

properties.long_name: Extent of the Roman Republic, A.D. 16
properties.event1:
A Roman army of 50,000 men commanded by Germanicus gains a great victory at Idistaviso, defeating the German war chief Arminius, and recovering the lost eagles of Varus' legions.
Germanicus employs the North Sea fleet to avoid dangerous rivers, embarking an army in the Rhine Delta, aboard circa 1,000 ships. He defeats the Germans at the Amisius river estuary and the Weser, but during its return, the Roman fleet is partially destroyed by storms.
properties.title_header: Year of the Consulship of Taurus and Libo

properties.long_name: Extent of the Roman Empire over all periods
properties.event1:
The boundary of the Roman Empire's frontier would flex back and forth throughout history.
The 200 year Pax Romana (Latin for "Roman Peace") during which the Roman Empire was relatively stable and peaceful began the accension of Caesar Augustus in 27 B.C. and ended with the death of Marcus Aurelius in A.D. 180.
properties.title_header: Regions occupied by Romans throughout history

properties.long_name: Extent of the Roman Republic, 60 B.C.
properties.rulers: Lucius Afranius; Quintus Caecilius Metellus Celer
properties.event1:
Gaius Julius Caesar suppresses an uprising and conquers all of Lusitania for Rome.
Creation of the First Triumvirate, an informal political alliance between Julius Caesar, Pompey the Great and Marcus Licinius Crassus.
properties.title_header: Year of the Consulship of Celer and Afranius

properties.long_name: Extent of the Roman Republic, 500 B.C.
properties.rulers: Manius Tullius Longus; Servius Sulpicius Camerinus Cornutus
properties.event1:
In the face of a potential Sabine invasion, the Senate passed a senatus consultum authorizing the consuls to appoint a dictator, a magistrate who held absolute power during a national emergency.
The Roman Republic used this political mothodology and appointed dictators in response to crises over several subsequent centuries.
properties.title_header: Year of the Consulship of Longus and Cornutus

properties.long_name: Extent of the Roman Republic, 133 B.C.
properties.rulers: Lucius Calpurnius Piso Frugi, Publius Mucius Scaevola
properties.event1:
The Tribune of the Plebs Tiberius Gracchus was beaten to death by a mob of senators led by the Pontifex Maximus Publius Cornelius Scipio Nasica Serapio
The Kingdom of Pergamum is deeded to Rome, Aristonicus starts a rebellion against this.
properties.title_header: Year of the Consulship of Scaevola and Frugi

properties.long_name: Extent of the Roman Empire, A.D. 117
properties.rulers: Caesar Nerva Traianus; Caesar Traianus Hadrianus Augustus
properties.event1:
Construction begins on the Pantheon in Rome.
The Roman Empire reaches its greatest extent.
properties.title_header: Year of the Consulship of Niger and Apronianus

properties.long_name: Extent of the Roman Empire, A.D. 69
properties.rulers: Servius Galba Caesar Augustus; Marcus Otho Caesar Augustus; Aulus Vitellius Germanicus Augustus; Caesar Vespasianus Augustus
properties.event1:
Year of the Four Emperors.
After Nero's death, Galba, Otho, Vitellius and Vespasian succeed each other as emperor during the year.
properties.title_header: Year of the Consulship of Augustus and Rufinus

properties.long_name: Extent of the Roman Empire, A.D. 84
properties.event1:
Possible date of the Battle of Mons Graupius (AD 83 or 84), in which Gnaeus Julius Agricola defeats the Caledonians.
The construction of the limes, a line of Roman fortifications from the Rhine to the Danube, is begun.
properties.title_header: Year of the Consulship of Augustus and Sabinus

properties.long_name: Extent of the Roman Empire, A.D. 102
properties.event1:
Emperor Trajan returns to Rome after a successful campaign against Dacia, through which he reestablishes clear Roman sovereignty over King Decebalus.
The port of Portus is enlarged.
properties.event2: Roman roads built during this period, spread primarily in the Roman province of Dacia (modern day Romania). In many ways, the imperial road network in Dacia exceeded that modern day Europe in terms of connecting to the rest of Europe, especially connecting to Greece and Macedonia. The Dacians and Romans built durable roads that withstood the test of time and many of these old roads are in great shape today despite their age.
properties.title_header: Year of the Consulship of Ursus and Sura

properties.long_name: Extent of the Roman Republic, 272 B.C.
properties.rulers: Lucius Papirius Cursor II; Spurius Carvilius Maximus II
properties.event1:
Pyrrhic War: Pyrrhus withdrew with his army to Epirus.
Taranto surrendered to Rome.
properties.title_header: Year of the Consulship of Cursor and Maximus

properties.long_name: Extent of the Roman Republic, 338 B.C.
properties.event1:
The Latin War ends with the Latin League being dissolved and the individual Latin cities having to accept Rome's terms.
With the fall of their chief city, Antium, to the Romans, the Volsci finally abandon their resistance against the Romans and accept an alliance with Rome.
properties.title_header: Year of the Consulship of Camillus and Maenius

properties.long_name: Extent of the Roman Empire, A.D. 47
properties.event1:
Corbulo orders the construction of the canal Fossa Corbulonis, between the Rhine and Meuse in the Netherlands, which connects the city Forum Hadriani (Voorburg)
Romans build the Traiectum fortification near the mouth of the Rhine, which will later grow to be the city of Utrecht.
properties.title_header: Year of the Consulship of Claudius and Vitellius
